data.content:
Your code **does not use `Thread.Abort`**, so there's no `PlatformNotSupportedException` risk here. It uses `Thread.Start`, `.Join`, and `Thread.Sleep` — all of which still work in .NET 8.

That said, the pattern should be modernized. Here's the recommended .NET 8 approach using `Task`/`Parallel`:

```csharp
public class SimpleWorker
{
    public async Task RunBatchAsync(List<WorkItem> items)
    {
        await Parallel.ForEachAsync(items, async (item, ct) =>
        {
            await Task.Run(() => Process(item), ct);
        });
    }

    private void Process(WorkItem item)
    {
        item.Result = ComputeResult(item.Input);
    }
}
```

**Key `Thread.Abort` migration points** (for when you encounter it elsewhere):

| .NET Framework | .NET 8 Replacement |
|---|---|
| `Thread.Abort()` | `CancellationToken` + cooperative cancellation |
| `Thread.Sleep()` | `await Task.Delay(ms, ct)` |
| Manual `Thread` + `Join` | `Task.Run` + `await` / `Parallel.ForEachAsync` |

If you find actual `Thread.Abort` calls in other code, replace them with a `CancellationTokenSource` pattern — the worker checks `ct.IsCancellationRequested` or calls `ct.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` at safe points.
